eas remain still largely untapped. Included here, and intended to further whet the palate, are figures from Sei Shōnagon, Christine de Pizan, and Mary Astell to Elizabeth Cady Stanton, Anna Julia Cooper, and Emma Goldman. Restoring female thinkers to the conversation of political philosophy is the primary goal of this book. Part I deploys a range of these thinkers to discuss the nature of political inquiry itself. Part II focuses on alternative approaches to and visions of core political ideas: equality, power, revolution, childhood, and community. While mainly an intellectual act of revival, this book also affects practical political life, because “remote and academic as they sometimes appear, debates about what to include in the canon ultimately touch almost everyone: students handed texts from lists of ‘great books’ to guide them . . . and citizens whose governments justify their actions with ideas from political texts deemed classic.";  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aFeminismxPolitical aspects. 0aWomen political scientistsxHistory. 0aWomen political scientists. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aAnna Julia Cooper.  aCanon Fodder.  aChristine de Pizan.  aElizabeth Cady Stanton.  aEmma Goldman.  aHannah Arendt.  aMary Astell.  aMary Wollstonecraft.  aSei Shōnagon.  aSimone de Beauvoir.  aWeiss.  aWestern political philosophy.  agender.  ahistory.  apolitics.  arhetoric.  athinkers.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271062808?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271062808423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271062808/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete e